    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "title": "When Consonants Meet: Consonant Clusters",
      "content": "You've learned all the vowels, all the consonants, and all the vowel marks. You can now read simple Sanskrit words! But you'll often encounter consonant clusters—sequences where two or more consonants appear WITHOUT a vowel between them. For example, in the word प्रिय (priya 'dear'), the consonants प (p) and र (r) combine directly before the vowel इ. Or in धर्म (dharma 'duty'), the consonants ध (dh) and र (r) combine, then म (m) follows. These are called CONJUNCT CONSONANTS or SAMYUKTĀKṢARA (संयुक्ताक्षर 'joined letters'). Sanskrit script represents consonant clusters in a special way: by removing the inherent 'a' vowel from all consonants EXCEPT THE LAST one, and combining them into a single visual unit. This lesson teaches you how conjuncts are formed and how to recognize the most common ones. This is the FINAL piece of Devanagari mastery—after this, you can read any Sanskrit text!",
      "order": 1
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "title": "How Conjuncts Are Formed: The Halanta (विराम Virāma) Mark",
      "content": "Remember: every consonant letter has an INHERENT 'a' vowel. क = ka, न = na, त = ta. To remove that inherent vowel and write just the consonant sound alone, you add a HALANTA mark (्), also called VIRĀMA. The halanta is a diagonal stroke below the consonant: क् = k (no vowel), न् = n (no vowel), त् = t (no vowel). When you want to write a consonant cluster, you: (1) Take the first consonant, (2) Add halanta to remove its vowel, (3) Attach it to the next consonant, (4) The combination may appear stacked vertically, side-by-side, or as a special ligature. Example: स् + त = स्त (sta); न् + त = न्त (nta); प् + र = प्र (pra). The LAST consonant in the cluster keeps its inherent vowel (or takes a vowel mark). Let's look at the three main types of conjunct forms:",
      "order": 2
    },
